<Author>Boardrider5050
<Content>Couldn't fault it for the price. I stayed here with my wife for 5 nights at the beginning of the month and overall it was fantastic.On first impression when we noticed the building site next door and two of the staff having a little row with eachother as walked in, we were a bit nervous about the place to say the least. Fortunately that was where our worries ended. The guy on reception was very good humoured and warned us about leaving our baggage near the doors as apparently it's been known for people to run in and grab them (ok this was a bit worring too but we didn't see any crime while we were in Barcelona) he told us we were lucky as we were in one of the newly refurbished rooms on the 4th floor and he wasn't wrong.The room (403) had a great new bathroom with two giant shower heads in a double shower and a very nice contempory wash basin and loo. The bed was very comfortable and there was a sliding door with a narrow balcony overlooking the square outside.Be warned some of the other floors are still in mid refurb so it might not be so great if you're staying there.The hotel is 2 mins from the harbour and the aquarium and 5 mins from the beach. You can walk along the harbour front and be at the end of La Rambla in about 10 - 15 mins and it's a very pleasant stroll.Barceloneta station is 50 yards away and using the subway is so easy you can get anywhere in minutes (although walking or hiring a bike is much more fun).Opposite the hotel is a restaurant called 7 Portes which has apparently been host to Winston Churchill and Che Guevara amongst many others and it's actually pretty good value considering how good the food and service is (best to get the early or book in advance as there was a bit of a queue there every night.) As for Barcelona itself I'd recommend Park Guell and Mount Tibidabo for a really energetic day out if the weather is good. Also the cable car to Montjuic that crosses the harbour had incredible views. Book in advance for the Palau de la musica and be prepared to queue for at least an hour if you want to catch the lift up the tower in Sagrada Familia but don't miss looking around it. Oh and find the open courtyard with the geese and palm trees at the cathedral it's surreal but beautiful.Look out for the 拢12 glass of beer if you have a drink in the middle of La Rambla, Estrella is great lager but that's mad.Leave the shopping until the evening as the days are short at the moment but take an extra case for all the clothes you buy!Anyway Barcelona is awesome and you could do a lot worse than the Oasis considering it came out one of the cheapest. Enjoy. 
