<Author>MountainLionsagogo
<Content>Go to Another Hotel Prior to our trip to Spain, we did our due diligence and checked out tripadvisor regarding the Hotel Oasis in Barcelona. The comments seemed to run in two extremes- glowing and bad. People liked it a lot, and had nothing but great things to report, or they did not have a good experience, which was also reported. Unfortunately, our experience fell in line with many of the experiences listed by the latter. Our RoomFor us a hotel is strictly utilitarian. Its a place to hang our hats at night. We do not book high end accommodations and we have little expectation of grand amenities. We stayed at the Oasis mid February 2008, and the room was stuffy-no just plain hot! The air conditioning did not work and a fan was already in the room. It did nothing but push the warm stale air. The room did have a window, but it opened to an air well that was capped on the roof. In order to sleep we rigged the door, so we were safe while it was ajar. This allowed for heavenly fresh air circulation. We wondered what this room would be like in the summer, uggg. Being energy conscious, the hotel had a motion sensor for the light in the hallway of the location of our room. The lights went on and off all night long. This was odd because our room was on a wing with only one other room, and it was vacant. Yep, you guessed it-a Rat!!!!BreakfastWe booked through Hotels.com, and a major selling point for the Oasis was that our booking included breakfast. If it did not, we would have gone elsewhere. We were only in Spain for two weeks and wanted to get out and see the country not hunt down restaurants for morning coffee and toast. We got our meal tickets for days one and two-no problem. We simply went to the desk and the Manager handed them to us. No talk of room number or money. The third day we went to the desk and a different clerk asked us for 8.90鈧?a piece ($24.48). All we said that breakfast was included in our package. To which he shot out of his chair and said 鈥淚 only work here, you must talk to the manager.鈥?We later had a giggle about this guy鈥檚 dramatic performance. We spoke to the manager the next morning; he crossed his arms and shook his head and said 鈥渘o鈥?then turned his back on us to do something else. We let it go, until we could take the issue up with Hotels.com, the company who took our money. Upon check out the manager tried to charge us for the first two days worth of breakfast. We told him it was included and had him look it up on Hotels himself. He let the issue go, by again folding his arms, shaking his head no, and walking away. Scary. We went on to Madrid for our second week in Spain. Our OpinionThe amount we paid for our room at the Hotel Oasis, was well in line with all of the surrounding hotels. We are not spoiled American tourists with expectations of grandeur when it comes to a room. We stay in hotels so we can see the World not a hotel, but we also do not expect to get a room too hot to sleep, see rats and experience the old bait and switch! This hotel has a great location and the property itself has potential to be really nice, with better management it could probably be a place to write home about, not a dissenting opinion on Tripadvisor.com. 
